ark Slope, Bedford-Stuyvesant, and Crown Heights, Gieseking shows how lesbian and queer neighborhoods have folded under the capitalist influence of white, wealthy gentrifiers who have ultimately failed to make room for them. Nevertheless, they highlight the ways lesbian and queer communities have succeeded in carving out spaces-and lives-in a city that has consistently pushed its most vulnerable citizens away.Beautifully written, A Queer New York is an eye-opening account of how lesbians and queers have survived in the face of twenty-first century gentrification and urban development.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aElectronic books. 0aGay people. 0aGays. 0aGender identity. 0aGender-nonconforming people. 0aIntersex people. 0aSexual minorities. 0aSexual minority culture. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / LGBT Studies / Gay Studies.2bisacsh  aBlack geographies.  aBrooklyn.  aConstellations.  aDisidentifications.  aFeminist theory.  aGentrification.  aGreenwich Village.  aLesbian.  aLines and orientations (Ahmed).  aManhattan.  aNeighbourhood.  aParadoxical space.  aPeople of color.  aProduction of space.  aQueer failure.  aQueer theory.  aQueers of color.  aRacism.  aTransgender and gender non-conforming people.  aUrban geography.  aWhiteness.40uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479803002.001.0001zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479803002zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479803002/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA